Interface Iterator<T>

All Known Implementing Classes:
AbstractReversibleIterator, AbstractUniversalIterator, ArrayIterator, CharacterIterator, ContinuousIterator, FileHierarchyIterator, FilteredIterator, GOFIteratorAdapter, IteratorAdapter, JEnumerationAdapter, JIteratorAdapter, JListIterator, JoiningIterator, LineIterator, ListIterator, MappingIterator, MatchResultIterator, NodeHierarchyIterator, NodeListIterator, ScannerIterator, StreamIterator, TreeIterator
public interface Iterator<T>

The Gang of Four's favorite iterator interface. Abstracts the traversal of an aggregate structure from the underlying representation. Note that method names have been modified from those given by the Gang of Four but the behavior is the same.

Use an iterator as follows: 

 Iterator<ExampleType> iter = getAnIterator();
 for(iter.reset(); !iter.isDone(); iter.advance()) {
        // do something with iter.current()
 }

Author:
Miorel-Lucian Palii

Method Detail

reset

void reset()
Moves this iterator to the beginning of the traversal. Some iterators cannot be reset once the iteration started. For example, an iterator over the lines of an input stream probably can't reread old lines. But all iterators should allow exception-less calls to this method before any calls to advance().

Throws:
IllegalStateException - if resetting this iterator is impossible

isDone

boolean isDone()
Checks whether this iterator has exhausted all the elements of its underlying traversal.

Returns:
whether all elements have been exhausted

advance

void advance()
Advances this iterator to the next element in the traversal. Behavior is undefined if the iterator is done.

current

T current()
Retrieves the current element in the traversal represented by this iterator.

Returns:
the current element in the traversal
